                  <b>Sathishkumar </b>pointed out that the Kalsofte ERP
                  distributes business logic across Common modules,
                  Class modules, and stored procedures — not just the
                  .frm file. He also highlighted that the TC
                  (Transaction Code) framework, which drives stock
                  direction and accounting entries across most of our
                  modules, is largely implemented inside stored
                  procedures and would be missed entirely if only the
                  form code was submitted to Claude.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Mariyaiya </b>raised a more fundamental concern:
                  that several PR, PO, and Service PO screens have
                  pending customer customisations in various stages of
                  stability. Submitting unstabilised code to Claude
                  would produce an FSD that documents an incomplete
                  version of the screen — and that instability would be
                  permanently carried into SPINRISE.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Mariyaiya then went further.</b> Before I could
                  even respond, he produced a detailed critical analysis
                  of the Purchase Requisition form (tmpPoindent.frm) — a
                  9,108-line VB6 form — and shared it with Muthuvel for
                  IST review. That document, which I have gone through
                  in detail, identified 3 Critical defects, 3 High
                  issues, 4 Medium issues, and 2 Low issues in the form
                  code. It also proposed the four-category validation
                  structure, the error message catalogue, the summary
                  scorecard, and the customer variation register — all
                  of which are now standard sections in the v2 FSD
                  template.<br>
                  <br>
                  This is what good teamwork looks like. You were given
                  a guide, you used it on a real form, you found its
                  limits, and you reported back with precision. V2 is
                  the direct result.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b><font size="4">What is new in v2<br>
                    </font></b><br>
                  For those who have read v1, here is what changed:<br>
                  <br>
                  Stage 0 is an entirely new mandatory phase that must
                  be completed before any FSD documentation begins. It
                  covers code stabilisation review, the screen readiness
                  checklist, what to collect before opening Claude (no
                  longer just the .frm file — now includes Common
                  modules, Class modules, and all stored procedures),
                  the TC framework reference table, the customer
                  variation register, and the dead code identification
                  step. Stage 0 is not optional. No FSD work begins on
                  any screen until Stage 0 is complete and TL-Dev has
                  signed off.<br>
                  <br>
                  The follow-up prompts grew from three to six. Three
                  new prompts were added: one for Common and Class
                  module logic, one for stored procedure business rules,
                  and one specifically for TC framework documentation.
                  These address the gap our first VB developer
                  identified.<br>
                  <br>
                  The FSD template expanded from 8 sections to 14
                  sections. The six new sections are the TC Framework,
                  Common and Class Module Dependencies, Error Message
                  Catalogue, Customer Variation Register, SPINRISE
                  Migration Recommendations, and the Summary Scorecard.
                  All six are mandatory for transaction screens.<br>
                  <br>
                  The review chain is updated to four levels with the
                  full IST structured questionnaire (IST-1 to IST-7)
                  that every Module Sr IST Member must answer for each
                  form they review.<br>
                  <br>
                  A new Section 8 documents eight known defect patterns
                  to actively search for in every VB6 form before
                  submitting to Claude: application-terminating End
                  statements, hardcoded customer IDs, SQL string
                  concatenation, dead code blocks, inconsistent
                  duplicate logic, hardcoded file paths, missing
                  transaction rollback, and typos in error messages.
                  Each pattern has the code signature to search for and
                  the action to take.<br>
                  <br>
                  Three quick reference cards are now at the back: the
                  Developer Daily Card, the four-column Reviewer
                  Checklist, and the new Defect Patterns Card. Print all
                  three and keep them at your desk.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>How I need each of you to use this guide<br>
                  </b><br>
                  <b>Module VB Developers:</b><br>
                  Section 3 (Stage 0) and Section 4 (the six steps and
                  six prompts) are your primary reference. Read them in
                  full. Before you begin any FSD, complete Stage 0 for
                  that screen. Do not skip the Customer Variation
                  Register. Do not submit dead code. Run all six
                  follow-up prompts, not just the ones you feel are
                  relevant.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Module Sr IST Members:</b><br>
                  Section 6, Level 1 and the IST Structured
                  Questionnaire (questions IST-1 to IST-7) are your
                  reference. For every FSD you review, answer all seven
                  questions. Section 8 (the defect patterns) is also
                  important for you — you are the person most likely to
                  know from site experience whether an
                  application-terminating behaviour or a hardcoded
                  customer variation has caused problems in practice.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>TL-IST:</b><br>
                  Section 6, Level 2. Your role is cross-module
                  consistency. Pay particular attention to whether TC
                  framework values and stored procedure business rules
                  are consistent with how the same logic is handled in
                  other modules you have implemented.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Project Manager:</b><br>
                  Section 6, Level 3. Before any FSD reaches the CEO,
                  confirm that all 14 sections are complete, all IST
                  questions are answered, the customer variation
                  register is filled, and the summary scorecard is
                  present. An incomplete FSD must be returned to the
                  developer, not passed forward.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>New Developer (Abinandan):</b><br>
                  Welcome again. This guide is your primary reference
                  for how SPINRISE development works. Start by reading
                  Section 3 (Stage 0) and Section 4. The defect patterns
                  in Section 8 will be particularly useful as you begin
                  reading Kalsofte VB6 code for the first time — you
                  will encounter all of these patterns. Now you know
                  what to do with each one.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Jr Web Dev team:</b><br>
                  Section 4, Step 6 and Section 7 are your references.
                  The approved FSD is your specification for React UI
                  generation. Read Section 7 carefully — it shows you
                  exactly what prompt to use when an FSD is handed to
                  you for code conversion.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b><font size="4">A word on how we got here</font></b><br>
                  <br>
                  When I shared v1, I said: this is version 1, your
                  feedback will shape version 2. You delivered. In less
                  than a week, the team produced two substantive pieces
                  of written feedback and one detailed 12-section
                  critical analysis of a real form. That is not normal.
                  Most teams wait to be asked.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>The quality of SPINRISE depends on the quality of
                    our FSDs.</b> The quality of our FSDs depends on the
                  rigour of our process. The rigour of our process
                  depends on each of you taking ownership of the part
                  only you can contribute — your domain knowledge, your
                  site experience, your module expertise.<br>
                  <br>
                  V2 reflects all of that. Bring the same energy to v2
                  that produced it.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b><font size="4">What I need from you </font></b><br>
                  <br>
                  Every developer and IST member: have read v2 in full.<br>
                  <br>
                  Module VB Developers: bring your Stage 0 readiness
                  assessment for your assigned module — identify which
                  screens are stable and which carry pending
                  customisations.<br>
                  <br>
                  Mariyaiya: bring the updated PR form critical analysis
                  with the v2 FSD template applied (14 sections).
                  Muthuvel’s IST review of that document, using the
                  IST-1 to IST-7 questionnaire, should be underway.<br>
                  <br>
                  TL-Dev: bring the list of screens across all Phase 1
                  modules that have pending customisations or open
                  corrections. This becomes the Stage 0 stabilisation
                  backlog.<br>
                  <br>
                  PM: activate the Stage 0 pre-sprint tracking in PULSE
                  360 for all Phase 1 modules.<br>
                  <br>
                  <b>Saturday is when we lock the v2 process and start.</b><br>
                  <br>
                  With appreciation for what this team has already
                  contributed, and confidence in what it will deliver,<br>
                  T Mani<br>
                  <br>
                  Attachment: SPINRISE_VB_FSD_Claude_Guide_v2.docx<br>
                  <br>
                  cc: Project Manager, TL-Dev, Full SPINRISE Team</p>
                <div class="moz-cite-prefix">On 29/03/2026 08:48 pm, CEO
                  wrote:<br>
                </div>
                <blockquote type="cite"
cite="mid:036f0737-960e-488e-b84c-8142e9220927@kalsofte.com">
                  <meta http-equiv="content-type"
                    content="text/html; charset=UTF-8">
                  <p>Dear SPINRISE Team,<br>
                    <br>
                    I am sharing with you today a guide that I have
                    personally put together with the assistance of
                    Claude.<br>
                    <br>
                    The document is attached: SPINRISE VB FSD Claude
                    Guide v1.docx<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>Please read it fully at your own pace and share
                      your feedback, at the earliest.</b></p>
                  <p><font size="4"><b>What this guide is</b></font><br>
                    <br>
                    This guide explains, in plain English, how each of
                    us uses Claude to convert a VB6 screen into a Form
                    Specification Document (FSD) — and how that FSD then
                    travels through our four-level review chain before
                    it is used to generate the new SPINRISE web screen.<br>
                    <br>
                    It covers:<br>
                      • What an FSD is and why we need one for every VB6
                    screen<br>
                      • The complete five-step process for the Module VB
                    Developer<br>
                      • The exact Claude prompt to use — ready to copy
                    and paste<br>
                      • The three follow-up questions to always ask
                    Claude after the first output<br>
                      • The four-level review chain: Module Sr IST →
                    TL-IST → PM → CEO<br>
                      • What each reviewer specifically checks and signs
                    off<br>
                      • Quick reference cards you can print and keep at
                    your desk<br>
                    <br>
                    <font size="4"><b>Who should read which sections<br>
                      </b></font><br>
                    <b>Module VB Developers:</b><br>
                    Section 3 is your primary reference. It walks you
                    through all five steps with the exact prompt, the
                    before-and-after example showing VB6 code versus
                    Claude’s plain-English output, and the three
                    follow-up questions. Read this section carefully
                    before you begin your first FSD. The quick reference
                    card in Section 7 is your daily desk guide.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>Module Sr IST Members:</b><br>
                    Section 4, Level 1 is written for you. It explains
                    exactly what your review covers, how to write your
                    annotations in the Word document using the [IST ADD]
                    and [IST CONFIRMED] tags, and what you must sign off
                    before the FSD moves to TL-IST.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>TL-IST:</b><br>
                    Section 4, Level 2 is your reference. You are the
                    second domain gate — the overall domain validation
                    after the Module Sr IST has done the first check.
                    Your experience across all modules and all customer
                    sites is what this level brings to the FSD.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>Project Manager:</b><br>
                    Section 4, Level 3. Your role is completeness — not
                    domain accuracy. By the time the FSD reaches you,
                    the domain has been validated by two levels. Your
                    question is: is this document thorough enough for a
                    developer to build the screen from scratch without
                    any ambiguity?<br>
                    <br>
                    <b>CEO:</b><br>
                    Section 4, Level 4 and Section 6. The CEO review is
                    the final domain authority gate. No technical skill
                    is needed. Only the question: does this FSD
                    accurately reflect how the business process was
                    designed to work, and does it carry forward the
                    knowledge that has been built over decades of
                    spinning ERP implementation?<br>
                    <br>
                    <font size="4"><b>A personal note</b></font><br>
                    <br>
                    This process — Document, Validate, Convert — is the
                    quality backbone of SPINRISE. Every web screen we
                    build is only as good as the FSD behind it.<br>
                    <br>
                    I have been saying this since we began: we are not
                    just migrating a software platform. We are
                    converting decades of accumulated spinning ERP
                    knowledge into a permanent, structured form that
                    will outlast the technology it runs on. Each FSD
                    that is reviewed and approved is a piece of that
                    knowledge preserved correctly.<br>
                    <br>
                    I want every one of you to understand the process
                    fully — not just the step that applies to your role,
                    but the complete journey from VB6 code to live
                    SPINRISE web screen. When everyone understands the
                    full chain, every handover between roles becomes
                    cleaner, faster, and more accurate.<br>
                    <br>
                    <b><font size="4">What I need from you</font></b><br>
                    <br>
                    Read the guide before this Saturday’s session.<br>
                    <br>
                    If any step is unclear, any instruction is
                    ambiguous, or any section does not match what you
                    experience in practice — write it down. <b>Share
                      your feedback as reply to this mail.</b><br>
                    <br>
                    This is version 1. Your feedback will shape version
                    2.<br>
                    <br>
                    With confidence in the team,<br>
                    T Mani<br>
                    <br>
                    Attachment: SPINRISE_VB_FSD_Claude_Guide_v1.docx</p>
